{"key":"processedPost-14169440","value":{"id":14169440,"first":14168898,"last":14169749,"when":1300901188,"utime":"03/23/11 08:26 PM","cleanedPost":"You drop the mycelium-covered agar right into the grains.&nbsp; Don't try to separate the mycelium from the agar.&nbsp; It needs the agar there to get a good jump off into the grains.<br />Mycelium will grow on the surface of agar, and this can be used to advantage.&nbsp; If you have bacteria on a plate, you can pour piping hot agar over the top of it, and when the mycelium climbs up through the new layer to reach the surface, shave it off and transfer to a new dish.&nbsp; This is a great way to separate mushroom mycelium from bacteria.<br />RR"}}